- Applying a translation of $a$ units in the direction of the negative $x$-axis to a function $f$ is shown as $f(x+a)$, and a translation of $b$ units in the direction of the negative $y$-axis is shown as $f(x)-b$.
  Therefore a translation of $\dfrac{\pi}{3}$ units in the direction of the negative $x$-axis would be $f\bigg(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\bigg)$. We have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  f\bigg(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\bigg) &= 3\cos\bigg(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\bigg)+\dfrac{9}{2}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Given that $A < \dfrac{9}{2}$, if we then apply a translation of $\dfrac{9}{2} - A$ units in the direction of the negative $y$-axis, we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  f\bigg(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\bigg) - \bigg(\dfrac{9}{2} - A\bigg) &= 3\cos\bigg(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\bigg)+\dfrac{9}{2} - \bigg(\dfrac{9}{2} - A\bigg) \\[10pt]
  &= 3\cos\bigg(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\bigg) + A \\[10pt]
  &= g(x)
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Therefore we have the following transformations in any order

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  T_1 &: \hspace{0.5em}\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{\text{translation of $\dfrac{\pi}{3}$ units in the direction of the negative $x$-axis}} \\[10pt]
  T_2 &: \hspace{0.5em}\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{\text{translation of $\dfrac{9}{2} - A$ units in the direction of the negative $y$-axis}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- We have $g(0)=\dfrac{9}{2}$. Solving for $A$, we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  3\cos\left(0+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\right)+A &= \dfrac{9}{2} \\[10pt]
  3\left(\dfrac{1}{2}\right) + A & = \dfrac{9}{2} \\[10pt]
  A & = 3 \\[-12pt]
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Therefore $g(x)=3\cos\left(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\right)+3$ , and the following inequalities hold:

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  -1\leq \cos\left(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\right) &\leq 1 \\[10pt]
  -3\leq 3\cos\left(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\right) &\leq 3 \\[10pt]
  0\leq 3\cos\left(x+\dfrac{\pi}{3}\right)+3 &\leq 6 \\[10pt]
  0\leq g(x) &\leq 6 \\[-12pt]
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Therefore the range of $g$ is $\answer{0\leq g(x) \leq 6}$

